self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/768"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"768"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88020"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"295"},{"type":"tags","id":"527"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4828"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7118"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7144"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38261"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42143"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43036"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44476"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105595","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105595"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 32-year-old woman presents to a rural hospital with a two day history of crampy lower abdominal pain and nausea. Her last menstrual period was four weeks ago and she takes the oral contraceptive pill. On examination she looks unwell with a blood pressure of 110/70 mmHg, pulse 110/min and temperature 37.8C. Her abdomen is soft, apart from localised tenderness and guarding in the right iliac fossa.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESome investigations should be considered to help establish the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following initial investigations is most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["White cell count","Ultrasound of the lower abdomen","Urine hCG and urinalysis","CT abdomen","C-reactive protein"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBased on the clinical picture, this women almost certainly has acute appendicitis. In all women of child-bearing age with abdominal pain, an ectopic pregnancy must be ruled out. An ectopic pregnancy may be life threatening and requires a prompt diagnosis. Thus, a urine beta-human chorionic gonadotrophin (\u003Cstrong\u003Eurine hCG\u003C/strong\u003E) is the most appropriate answer. A positive b-HCG is a level above 20mIU/mL and, in intra-uterine pregnancies, should double every 48 hours for the first 8 weeks gestation. A serum b-hCG may take several hours, but a urine hCG can be analysed as soon as the urine sample is collected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst an \u003Cstrong\u003Eultrasound of the lower abdomen\u003C/strong\u003E can identify an ectopic pregnancy, as well as assess for fluid within the pelvic cavity, it is not the most appropriate initial investigation. It remains important to consider in the work up of an ectopic pregnancy as its able to identify the ectopic site. Abdominal ultrasonography is being used in cases of suspected appendicitis with increasing frequency, however it is unlikely that such resources would be available in a rural hospital.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst \u003Cstrong\u003Ecomputed tomography (CT) of the abdomen\u003C/strong\u003E is readily available in most hospitals, it is not the most appropriate initial investigation. Unnecessary exposure to radiation should be avoided, especially in pregnant women. All women of child bearing age should receive a pregnancy test prior to a CT for investigation of abdominal pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst a \u003Cstrong\u003EC-reactive protein\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Ewhite cell count\u003C/strong\u003E are important in the work-up of this patient, they are not initial or diagnostic investigations.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Always rule out pregnancy when assessing abdominal tenderness in women of childbearing age"],"references":["Schuur JD, Tibbetts SA, Pines JM. Pregnancy testing in women of reproductive age in US emergency departments, 2002 to 2006: assessment of a national quality measure. Ann Emerg Med. 2010;55(5):449-457.e2. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19931941/","Minnerop MH, Garra G, Chohan JK, Troxell RM, Singer AJ. Patient history and physician suspicion accurately exclude pregnancy. Am J Emerg Med. 2011;29(2):212-5.. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20825808/","Baker M, dela Cruz J. Ectopic Pregnancy, Ultrasound. [Updated 2023 Jan 16]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482192/","Kao LY, Scheinfeld MH, Chemyak V, et al.. Beyond Ultrasound: CT and MRI of Ectopic Pregnancy. American Journal of Roentgenology. 2014;202(4):904-911. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24660723/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88020"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"768"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88020","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88020"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-10T21:17:00+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-10T21:19:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"768"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105595"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"headi